                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-158047 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-brain tag-brain-cancer tag-senses-and-sensation tag-tumors tag-vertigo des-brain des-brain-cancer des-senses-and-sensation des-tumors des-vertigo" id="post-158047">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Literal Balance, Life Balance</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Adrienne Brodeur			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-09-17T07:21:46+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 17, 2015 3:21 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 17, 2015 3:21 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The first time I fell, last autumn, I chalked it up to a combination of fatigue, clumsiness and bad luck. I had stolen some time away from work and chores, and I was goofing around with my 6-year-old, who was chasing
                                        me on his scooter. Attempting to escape, I leapt onto a log, which wobbled ever so slightly, and down I went.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While listening attentively to the emergency-room doctor, who showed me X-rays of my broken wrist and demonstrated the proper use of a splint, it didn&#x2019;t occur to me to mention the peculiar sensation I&#x2019;d
                                        experienced during my fall. I hadn&#x2019;t been aware of a downward trajectory. Instead, I&#x2019;d felt a gravity-less feeling, more spacewalk than fall, with no awareness of my relationship to the ground until
                                        impact. But the experience was so fleeting it seemed to defy recognition, let alone warrant medical attention.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It wasn&#x2019;t until my second fall less than a month later that I realized something other than ineptitude was going on. I was marching across a Vermont meadow when my son pointed up at the Big Dipper and shouted,
                                        &#x201C;Look, Mommy!&#x201D; The moment I raised my eyes toward the stars, I started to float and my feet lost traction with the earth, as if following the trajectory of my head. I ended up observing the spinning
                                        constellation from flat on my back. I decided to call my doctor.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Soon enough, I found myself on a narrow, cushioned table in a cold room, being readied for an M.R.I., a procedure my doctor explained would &#x201C;rule things out.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-158047"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/09/17/opinion/17private/17private-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/09/17/opinion/17private/17private-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/09/17/opinion/17private/17private-blog480.jpg" id="100000003916795"
                                                    width="480" height="613" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="613">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Vivienne Flesher</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Later, on the computer screen in the neurosurgeon&#x2019;s office, my brain blossomed like a flower in a child&#x2019;s flipbook as the doctor scrolled through the images. He stopped to show me a white dot, which grew
                                        and diminished over the course of several dozen slides.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;That&#x2019;s it,&#x201D; he said, matter-of-factly, framing it in the cross hairs of his cursor. &#x201C;The size of a small blueberry.&#x201D; A blueberry? It was, in fact, a brain tumor, a vestibular schwannoma,
                                        parked on the cranial nerve behind my ear that governs balance and hearing. Over the coming months, I got opinions from three top brain surgeons, each of whom had a different solution as to how to remove the tumor
                                        or stop its growth: traditional brain surgery, radiation or gamma knife. I had na&#xEF;vely thought that there would be consensus, a single best solution.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Four M.R.I.s later, I understand that while it is not a diagnosis anyone wants, as far as brain tumors go, mine is as good as it gets. The tumor is slow-growing and most likely benign, which will enable me to put off
                                        treatment, a good thing as surgery can leave me with symptoms worse than those I currently experience: total deafness in my right ear, more severe balance problems and possible damage to my facial nerve, which could
                                        leave me unable to blink or swallow.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like many people whose lives are a juggling act &#x2014; my balls include young children, elderly parents and a busy job directing a literary organization &#x2014; I&#x2019;ve spent my fair share of time contemplating
                                        work and life balance, that elusive spot where supposedly, if you can stay present and embrace the &#x201C;off&#x201D; switch, you will find calm amid the chaos of competing demands. No easy feat in today&#x2019;s
                                        cult of productivity. Like most working mothers, I&#x2019;ve had limited success in the life balance arena, careening instead from joy to overwhelmed and back again.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But no matter now. My focus on life balance has taken a back seat to my obsession with real balance: What keeps us standing? What goes wrong when we fall? And why do so few people seem to understand how it works? About
                                        six months ago, I began logging my stumbles and near tumbles and found patterns.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Oddly, the place I most frequently experienced that disoriented, &#x201C;floaty&#x201D; feeling was in the shower. A close second was when I stooped to give my children bedtime kisses. The rotary vertigo happened each
                                        and every time I texted or checked email while walking, as well as when I looked anywhere other than the direction I was going.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Unlike your five senses, all of which rely on a seemingly obvious instrument to do their respective jobs &#x2014; eyes, nose, tongue, ears and skin &#x2014; normal balance depends on the coordinated sensory input of
                                        three distinct systems: vision, proprioception and vestibular. Each provides the brain with critical information about the body&#x2019;s orientation to the ground and the earth&#x2019;s gravitational pull.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Vision is perhaps the most straightforward element of the balance triumvirate. It tells the brain how the body is oriented in relation to other markers like vertical trees, buildings and poles. It is why a balance posture
                                        in yoga, such as the tree pose, becomes more difficult when your eyes are closed, or why you might experience vertigo in high places, where there are fewer visual cues.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Proprioception, as the word itself suggests, is a bit more complicated; sensors known as proprioceptors in muscles, tendons and joints throughout your body let your brain know where body parts are situated in space.
                                        This is why, if your ankles flex as you walk, your brain is able to interpret that the ground is inclining without necessarily having a visual cue.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The vestibular system &#x2014; the source of my problems &#x2014; is even more complex.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Located in the inner ear at the entryway to the skull, it is protected by some of the hardest bone in the body. Aptly known as &#x201C;the labyrinth,&#x201D; it looks like a miniature &#x201C;Star Trek&#x201D; space
                                        station with two sacs and three looping semicircular canals arranged at roughly right angles to one another. Fluid moves through the labyrinth stimulating tiny hairs, which act as sensors that monitor the position
                                        and movement of your head, sending the brain information about gravity, motion and your body&#x2019;s relationship to earth.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What I know about my own condition is that any sudden head shift can result in extreme vertigo, the kind that puts motion into the stars, as van Gogh depicted in his painting &#x201C;The Starry Night.&#x201D; (Some
                                        experts now believe van Gogh suffered from M&#xE9;ni&#xE8;re&#x2019;s disease, a disorder of the inner ear that causes spontaneous vertigo.)</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With a malfunctioning vestibular system, I have to rely more heavily on inputs from the other two systems: proprioception and vision, to keep myself upright. I find myself in precarious situations when one of those
                                        becomes compromised, too, as happens when the ground becomes unstable beneath my feet or when I shut my eyes. In a nanosecond, my equilibrium is gone, along with any awareness of how my body is situated in space.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the shower, if I spend a moment concentrating on the porcelain under my feet, it somehow activates my powers of proprioception and prompts my brain to keep my body upright. Stay standing, I tell myself. When I bend
                                        over to kiss my children good night, I now put a hand on the bedpost as a reference point and my body maintains its gravitational bearings. The improbable consequence of my dodgy equilibrium is that it has forced
                                        me to lead a slower, more present, and &#x2014; dare I say it? &#x2014; more balanced existence.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In this way, my brain tumor has emerged as a tiny Zen master. Everything about it &#x2014; from the intermittent fear it engenders, to the M.R.I.s it requires, to my daily struggle for physical balance &#x2014; has
                                        made achieving that other kind of balance, inner balance, more possible. I can no longer coast through my daily life multitasking as I go: reading headlines as I walk, looking both ways as I dash across the street,
                                        showing up for good-night kisses, but being absent all the same.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even my most mundane actions have to be performed with intention, or I risk embarrassing, if not dire, consequences. I have yet to find any virtue in having to come to a complete, robotic stop in order to turn my head,
                                        and I&#x2019;m more terrified than I care to admit about the surgery that I will one day face.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That said, my need for physical touch to stay vertical &#x2014; be it feeling the ground beneath my feet or holding a friend&#x2019;s arm as we stroll &#x2014; has been life altering. I feel fortunate to be physically
                                        incapable of texting while I walk (we should all be so lucky) and for the need to be present, and I mean truly present, for each and every good-night kiss.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Adrienne Brodeur is a writer and creative director of Aspen Words, a program of the Aspen Institute.</em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 09/20/2015, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">8</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the
                                                headline: The Brain Tumor As Zen Master.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
                                </div>
